<br>
&quot;Friends&quot; is the #1 rated show in the U.S.  I don't ask Jennifer Aniston her views on renewing China's Most-favored Trade status.<br>
<br>
I'm not flaming either... don't get me wrong. I've just found that FOX news (mainly papers, mind you...) has routinely glossed over important facts, critical analysis, and balanced reporting for quick jabs at pols (hate that term - I think it's a NY thing), heated rhetoric, and openly sniping at any Time-Warner holding while advancing the Murdoch agenda.<br>
<br>
Which is fine, in its own way, so long as it is in the open.<br>
<br>
What's funny about the liberal-conservative argument is that they both rally around the Constitution while insisting the other doesn't.  *shrug* The Constitution is not outdated... like horoscopes, it is written in a vague enough manner so that the same precepts can be used to argue widely differing viewpoints - a Good Thing - and has a built in mechanism for self-correction should parts ever become outdated.  Never a question as to the document's worth.<br>
<br>
Now the &quot;well ordered militia&quot; that is supposed to have the right to bear arms?  That's up for discussion.  As is how &quot;well ordered milita&quot; became &quot;the general populace,&quot; how militia groups became criminalized, and how &quot;bear arms&quot; can be taken as &quot;carrying concealed handguns with Black Rhino bullets.&quot;  But, that's an argument for another thread.<br>
<br>
In the interest of full disclosure, I vote Socialist, and I have no qualms whatsoever about leaning to the left or to the right.   Politics is a balancing act.... gotta have weight on both sides to make it work.  I believe in diplomacy over the bomb, and in the power of an informed electorate.<br>
<br>
Oh, and I meant to say this in the original post.  Bush isn't a terrorist, and I'm not willing to say he's a crappy president YET.  I will say, however, that he is one of the worst statesmen I have ever seen in my life.<br>
