<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=205913">Quit Staring at Me.  Here is a picture.<BR><LEFT><img src="http://www.fireandfury.org/sigs/Zsuzsana.jpg"></A></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uidril01.showPublicProfile?language=EN>idril01</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/18/02 4:42:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1582.topic&index=42>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Confessions of a Curmudgeon</span><hr size=1> I disagree.  When something is wrong with what a Democrat is proposing, with public schools, with environmental protection efforts, with social issues, Fox News will go after it like a pit bull.<br>
<br>
When something is wrong with a big business executive robbing his shareholders blind, a major religious institution embroiled in a sex abuse scandal, or the vice president refusing to turn over documents regarding how much influence businesses like Exxon had in setting US energy policy, they give it the soft touch.<br>
<br>
I would prefer to watch CNN when I get home from work, but unfortunately, all CNN has on when I do so is Larry King Live, so I end up watching either Fox or MSNBC.  Frankly, neither of these are exactly bastions of journalistic integrity.  The editorial bias of the network is clear, even in the “hard” news reporting.  Having two guys debate opposite political viewpoints is nice, but it cannot make up for the editorial slant in the day to day news coverage.<br>
<br>
I watched Fox News the night after the Israelis dropped a bomb on an apartment building in the West Bank in order to kill the leader of a Palestinian militant group.  Of course in the process they killed half a dozen innocent people, including children.  The news coverage showed the wreckage, showed the Israeli Prime Minister expressing remorse for the loss of life, then showed Palestinian protestors burning American flags.  The viewer at home was left with the impression it was an unfortunate accident that occurred as Israel went after a terrorist, and that all Palestinians are terrorists who hate Americans for no reason.<br>
<br>
What the newscast didn’t mention was why those teenagers might blame America for what happened, namely the “made in the USA” logo on the bomb, and on the plane that dropped it.  Or why Palestenians are pissed off enough to strap high explosives to themselves and blow themselves up in a shopping mall, namely being driven into refugee camps as a result two foreign powers decided to re-appropriate their land in 1949 for the creation of a new country, without their consent.  <br>
<br>
Most certainly the terrorist acts were not justified, and the news coverage should never imply that they were.  But they should at least try and explain the “why” behind the events, from both sides point of view.   And that’s where Fox, and pretty much every other major broadcast media outlet, fails, either by accident or intent.  <br>
<br>
When you ask “why” you start to raise questions that make us uncomfortable, and these days our news media is much more interested in selling advertising than in challenging Americans to learn more about their nation and the world in which we live.<br>
