k thx la~ <p><B>Zsuzsana Dracul</B><BR><I>Phantasmist of 60 Seductions</I><BR>
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=205913">Quit Staring at Me.  Here is a picture.<BR><LEFT><img src="http://www.fireandfury.org/sigs/Zsuzsana.jpg"></A></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uidril01.showPublicProfile?language=EN>idril01</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/18/02 5:26:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1582.topic&index=45>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Confessions of a Curmudgeon</span><hr size=1> The formation if Israel in 1949 is an issue I'm pretty conversant on.  At the time Palestine was a colony of Great Britain, and had little say in the matter.  Like all properties of the British Crown at the time, there was no democratic process for the people being ruled.  Britain, suffering from enormous economic problems following World War II, was beginning to divest itself of colonies around the world, particularly troublesome ones (militants supporting the creation of a Jewish state in Palestine had run a fairly low-intensity guerilla conflict against the Brits for years).<br>
<br>
The decision to re-appropriate some of the land within the borders of Palestine for the creation of Israel was made largely by the United States and Britain, but covered under the auspices of the newly-formed United Nations.  The average Palestinian had about as much say in the process as the average Native American had in the settlement of the American West.  <br>
<br>
Since that time Israel has expanded it's borders through military acquisition and occupation of Gaza and the West Bank (though Israel was certainly within its rights to defend its citizens from foreign aggression, which is what it was doing when it acquired them).  Unfortunately hundreds of thousands of Palestinians were forced from their homes during these conflicts, and Israel has never allowed them to return.  Worse (at least from the view of the Palestinians), Israel now has a settlement program that aims to create new communities on this same land.<br>
<br>
The BBC has an excellent web site on the Israeli-Palestinian conflict.  It is well worth checking out for anyone trying to figure out the mess in the Middle East:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/in_depth/world/2001/israel_and_palestinians/timeline/">news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english.../timeline/</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
There is no &quot;right&quot; side on the Israeli/Palestinian conflict.  Things have gotten so bad I'm not sure it can ever be solved.  But Americans (and others) who are watching it from afar should be informed that their are two sides to the story, and both have fairly compelling reasons for what they are doing.  It is not as simple as labeling one a &quot;terrorist&quot; or the other an &quot;aggressor&quot;.  And we should also understand the role that we have played, and continue to play, in fueling the conflict, and all the assorted nastiness that spins off from it around the world.<br>
